ania and O1 layers of natural coniferous forests which showed an opposite trend. Adding stand age to the regression equations  increased the predictive capability of the regression equations based on elevation only. The regression equations developed in this study can be used along with the tree aboveground biomass derived from forest timber surveys to estimate the regional forest aboveground biomass and carbon accumulation in Taiwan.</para></abstract><keywordSet><keyword>aboveground biomass</keyword></keywordSet><keywordSet><keyword>forest type</keyword></keywordSet><keywordSet><keyword>forest floor</keyword></keywordSet><coverage scope="document"><geographicCoverage scope="document"><geographicDescription>Taiwan</geographicDescription><boundingCoordinates><westBoundingCoordinate>119.75</westBoundingCoordinate><eastBoundingCoordinate>122.25</eastBoundingCoordinate><northBoundingCoordinate>25.375</northBoundingCoordinate><southBoundingCoordinate>21.5</southBoundingCoordinate></boundingCoordinates></geographicCoverage><temporalCoverage scope="document"><singleDateTime><calendarDate>2001</calendarDate></singleDateTime></temporalCoverage></coverage><contact scope="document"><references>1164943228297</references></contact><methods><methodStep><description><section><title>sampling</title><para>Plantations of Taiwan red pine, Taiwania, Cryptomeria, China-fir, and Taiwan red cypress were selected in working circles of Taiwan Forestry Bureau, based on the plantation data bank of the Bureau. During November and December 2001, three forest floor samples with 50 cm * 50 cm were taken in each of selected plantations and nearby natural stands, when possible, and separated into O1(i.e. L) and O2(i.e. F and H) layers in the field.</para></section></description></methodStep></methods><access authSystem="knb" order="denyFirst" scope="document"><allow><principal>public</principal><permission>read</permission></allow></access><dataTable id="1164961964075" scope="document"><entityName>